title.narrative: 5.1 DATA AND EVIDENCE ON CHILD DEPRIVATION

description.narrative: 5.1 Government has increased capacity to use disaggregated data and evidence related to child deprivation., which contributes to Cross-Sectoral - Monitoring, Data And Situation Analyses, Evaluation, Evaluation (Covid), Learning, Skills, Participation And Engagement, Learning, Skills, Participation And Engagement (Covid), Reducing Child Poverty, Reducing Child Poverty (Covid), Research. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Evaluations, Research And Data, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2023, more children benefit from quality child-sensitive policies and social protection programmes, which reduce their vulnerability to multidimensional poverty and the impact of economic shocks and disasters

title.narrative: 5.1 Government has increased capacity to use disaggregated data and evidence related to child deprivation.

description.narrative: UNICEF supported the Government of Sierra Leone to launch the national mid-term census which will be completed in 2022 and reinforces and improves the government’s capacity to use disaggregated data and evidence related to child deprivation by providing updated data on the aforementioned and national sampling frames for future household surveys. In addition, in 2021 the government of Sierra Leone submitted its third report under the Voluntary National Review (VNR) mechanism with UNICEF technical and financial support. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:03/02/2022
